result:
I've now analyzed the full change. The diff scopes `--resume-last` and the resume-candidate lookup to the current Claude session (via the newly-exported `filterJobsForCurrentSession`/`getCurrentSessionId`), and gates the on-disk thread fallback behind `sessionId ? null : findLatestTaskThread(...)`. The three new tests confirm the intended session-isolation behavior, and job records are stamped with `sessionId` so same-session resume still works.

The change is largely coherent and well-tested. The one issue I can identify is a behavioral inconsistency introduced by disabling the disk fallback when a session is active:

- `task-resume-candidate` advertises any non-active task (including `failed`/`cancelled`) with a `threadId` as an available resume candidate (line 872-878).
- But `resolveLatestTrackedTaskThread` only accepts `status === "completed"` tracked tasks (line 323), and now, when a session id is set, returns `null` instead of falling back to `findLatestTaskThread` (line 328). Previously the disk fallback would have recovered a failed/cancelled task's persisted thread.

So in session mode, after a failed (but thread-persisted) task, the UI hint says a resumable task exists, yet `/codex:task --resume-last` errors with "No previous Codex task thread was found." Before this change that path resumed successfully via the disk fallback.

```json
{
  "claims": [
    {
      "file": "plugins/codex/scripts/codex-companion.mjs",
      "line": 328,
      "description": "Gating the findLatestTaskThread fallback behind `sessionId ? null` means that, when a Claude session id is set, a failed/cancelled task that has a persisted thread can no longer be resumed (resolveLatestTrackedTaskThread only accepts status==='completed'), even though handleTaskResumeCandidate still advertises it as an available resume candidate — so the resume-candidate hint and `--resume-last` now disagree, and same-session resume of a non-completed task regresses from working to throwing 'No previous Codex task thread was found.'"
    }
  ]
}
```
